    "faq.q3": "Will resizing to a smaller max dimension blur my image?",
    "faq.a3": "Choosing a max dimension like 1920px or 1280px permanently reduces the pixel width and height of images larger than that value, which is exactly what shrinks the file size further — a 6000×4000 photo scaled down to 1920×1280 has far fewer pixels to store. On a screen, browser, or social media post the result usually looks identical, since most displays can't show more detail than that anyway. But the resize can't be undone, and it will look soft if you print the file large or zoom in a lot afterward — keep \"No resize\" selected if you need to preserve the full original resolution and only want the quality slider to reduce file size.",
